# Source And Literature Scan Notes

This is a representative scan, not an exhaustive archive of every Hall, ion,
plasma, sail, and tether paper ever published. The field spans thousands of
papers across AIAA, IEPC, NASA NTRS, ESA, JPL, Princeton, University of
Michigan PEPL, and many national programs.

## Equations Implemented

- Momentum thrust: `F = mdot * ve`
- Specific impulse: `Isp = ve / g0`
- Power-limited electric propulsion: `F = 2 * eta * P / ve`
- Rocket equation: `delta-v = ve * ln(m0 / m1)`
- Electrostatic ion speed: `ve = sqrt(2 * Z * e * V / mi)`
- Child-Langmuir current density estimate for gridded ion optics
- Pulsed thruster energy: `E = 0.5 * C * V^2`
- Pulsed average thrust: `F = impulse_bit * repetition_rate`
- MPD self-field rough estimate using a Maecker-style geometry factor
- Applied-field Lorentz thrust estimate: `F = I * B * L`
- Solar sail pressure at 1 AU using the reflective-sail baseline
- Photon sail force: `F = momentum_factor * eta * P / c`
- Electrodynamic tether Lorentz force and motional EMF
- Fusion fuel power and burn rate from reaction energy density
- Direct-fusion jet-power closure using target exhaust velocity or entered mass
  flow
- Radiator sizing from Stefan-Boltzmann heat rejection
- Pulsed fusion/nuclear-pulse average thrust and impulse-bit estimates

## Representative Papers And Technical References

- Dan M. Goebel and Ira Katz, *Fundamentals of Electric Propulsion: Ion and
  Hall Thrusters*. Core reference for ion/Hall physics, ion acceleration,
  losses, and efficiency accounting.
- NASA / AEPS literature: Advanced Electric Propulsion System and HERMeS
  Hall-thruster performance class, including NASA/TM-2018-219761.
- NASA NSTAR and NEXT ion-thruster literature: Deep Space 1, Dawn, and NEXT
  gridded-ion performance ranges.
- Jacob Simmonds and Yevgeny Raitses, "Performance of Oscillating Plasma
  Thrusters", arXiv:2002.09732.
- Adam R. Patel, Yunping Zhang, and Alexey Shashurin, "Liquid-Fed Pulsed
  Plasma Thruster for Propelling Nanosatellites", arXiv:1907.00169.
- T. C. Underwood, W. Riedel, and M. A. Cappelli, "Dual Mode Operation of a
  Hydromagnetic Plasma Thruster to Achieve Tunable Thrust and Specific
  Impulse", arXiv:2103.14532.
- Matthew Han and Hannah Rana, "Applied-Field Magnetoplasmadynamic Thrusters
  for Deep Space Exploration", arXiv:2410.17478.
- Ethan Kahn, "Electrospray Thruster Plume Impingement on CubeSat Solar
  Arrays", arXiv:2510.05084.
- Grover A. Swartzlander Jr., "Theory of Radiation Pressure on a Diffractive
  Solar Sail", arXiv:2206.10052.
- NASA / MSFC, *Tethers in Space Handbook*, for electrodynamic tether
  fundamentals and mission concepts.
- Direct Fusion Drive literature from Princeton Plasma Physics Laboratory /
  Princeton Satellite Systems mission studies, including D-He3 fusion drive
  assumptions.
- NASA NIAC and university work on magneto-inertial fusion rockets and pulsed
  fission-fusion propulsion concepts.
- General antimatter propulsion estimates are included only as idealized energy
  bookkeeping, not as a practical storage or engine design.

## Design Warning

This app is useful for first-pass sizing and comparison. It is not a
flight-qualified design code. Real non-chemical propulsion work needs detailed
plasma modeling, high-voltage design, erosion/lifetime modeling, thermal design,
materials limits, plume impingement analysis, structural dynamics, attitude
coupling, power processing, and trajectory optimization.

The experimental/fusion tab is the most speculative part of the tool. It is
intended to help compare orders of magnitude, radiator penalties, thrust/power
tradeoffs, and mission mass sensitivity.
